  const vMods = [
    { slug:null, n:"VM01", title:"Entrepreneurial Mindset & Business Fundamentals", tagline:"How real businesses start. How founders think.", sub:"Deliverable: Problem statement + customer profile + initial value hypothesis",
      body:"Market sizing, idea validation, problem-solution fit, and different business models for specific markets. Students learn how to identify meaningful problems, evaluate opportunities, validate assumptions, and design business models capable of creating real value. Through founder case studies and practical exercises, they develop the core venture thesis that will guide their work throughout the semester.",
      learn:["The entrepreneurial mindset — how founders identify problems, opportunities, and market gaps","Opportunity assessment — distinguishing between interesting ideas and scalable opportunities","Idea validation — testing whether an idea is worth pursuing before building","Market sizing — TAM, SAM, SOM, and what those numbers tell investors","Problem-solution fit — defining a problem precisely and matching it to a solution","Business model fundamentals — how ventures create, deliver, and capture value","Customer profiling — identifying users, buyers, and decision-makers","Value hypothesis development — articulating why customers would choose your solution"] },
    { slug:null, n:"VM02", title:"Competitive Analysis & Market Research", tagline:"Who else is doing this. Why would a customer choose you.", sub:"Deliverable: Competitive Map · Differentiation Statement · Customer Research Findings",
      body:"Students learn how to conduct customer interviews and what to listen for, how to evaluate competitors, understand market dynamics, and gather meaningful insights. The goal is to move beyond assumptions and build a venture based on evidence rather than opinion.",
      learn:["Competitive mapping — identifying direct, indirect, and substitute competitors","Porter’s Five Forces — analyzing industry attractiveness and competitive pressure","SWOT analysis — assessing strengths, weaknesses, opportunities, and threats","Value proposition design — why customers should choose you and creating meaningful differentiation","Primary market research — conducting customer interviews and surveys","Customer insight analysis — identifying patterns, pain points, and unmet needs","Market positioning — understanding where a venture fits within the competitive landscape","Differentiation strategy — building advantages competitors cannot easily replicate"] },
    { slug:null, n:"VM03", title:"Marketing, Branding & Customer Psychology", tagline:"Who is your customer. How do you reach them.", sub:"Deliverable: Brand Marketing Portfolio · Messaging Framework · Customer Acquisition Plan",
      body:"Students learn how successful ventures attract attention, build trust, and create demand in competitive markets. Through practical exercises, case studies, and real-world examples, they learn how to build not just a company, but a brand that stands out. Students explore brand strategy, storytelling, customer psychology, and competitive positioning to understand why some ventures break through the noise while others are ignored.\n\nThe module guides students through the creation of a complete Venture Launch Portfolio, including brand positioning, logo concepts, visual identity systems, brand guidelines, mission and vision statements, taglines and mottos, tone of voice frameworks, storytelling narratives, and customer-facing messaging. Students learn how to establish and manage professional social media profiles, create advertising accounts, develop content strategies, and build the foundational marketing infrastructure required for launch.\n\nBy the end of the module, students will have developed the positioning, messaging, branding assets, and customer acquisition foundations needed to reach the right audience, communicate value clearly, build credibility, and create a brand that customers recognize, remember, trust, and advocate for.",
      learn:["Customer segmentation — defining your ideal customer with precision, not generality","Brand identity portfolio — name, positioning, voice, visual presence, and what your brand actually stands for","Customer acquisition fundamentals — how businesses attract their first customers","The marketing funnel — awareness, consideration, conversion, and retention","Consumer psychology — why people buy, hesitate, trust, compare, and decide","Persuasion principles — Cialdini’s six drivers: reciprocity, commitment, social proof, authority, liking, scarcity","Digital marketing channels — social media, content marketing, email, SEO, paid acquisition","Messaging and copywriting — writing headlines, offers, and calls to action that convert","Positioning strategy — occupying a distinct, defensible place in the customer’s mind","Storytelling in business — using narrative to create engagement","Growth experiments — testing marketing ideas with limited resources","Brand consistency — creating a coherent customer experience across touchpoints"] },
    { slug:null, n:"VM04", title:"AI as a Business Tool", tagline:"Not a threat. A tool. Learn to use it better than anyone in the room.", sub:"Deliverable: AI-Built Market Research Report · AI Competitive Intelligence Brief · Venture AI Workflow Stack",
      body:"Artificial intelligence is rapidly becoming one of the most powerful leverage tools available to founders, executives, and professionals. The advantage no longer belongs to the person who works the longest hours — it belongs to the person who can combine human judgment with intelligent systems.\n\nStudents learn how entrepreneurs and business leaders use AI to accelerate research, analyze markets, understand competitors, generate content, improve decision-making, streamline operations, and increase productivity. Rather than treating AI as a novelty, students learn how to integrate it into real business workflows and apply it directly to their own venture.\n\nThe module focuses on practical execution. Students use AI to conduct market research, generate customer insights, build competitive intelligence reports, develop marketing assets, create investor presentation materials, and automate repetitive tasks. Equally important, they learn where AI breaks down, where hallucinations occur, and why human judgment remains the ultimate competitive advantage.",
      learn:["AI-powered market research — analyzing industries, trends, customers, and competitors at scale","Prompt engineering for business — designing prompts that produce useful, reliable, and actionable outputs","Competitive intelligence workflows — gathering, organizing, and synthesizing information faster than traditional methods","AI for marketing and content creation — generating messaging, copy, campaigns, and creative assets","AI-assisted presentation and pitch development — building investor decks, reports, and business documents","Workflow automation — identifying repetitive tasks and designing systems and agents that save time","AI for customer analysis — uncovering patterns, feedback themes, and customer insights","Evaluating AI tools and platforms — understanding strengths, limitations, costs, and use cases","AI ethics and responsible use — privacy, bias, intellectual property, and transparency","Human judgment as a competitive advantage — knowing when to trust AI, when to challenge it, and when to ignore it entirely"] },
    { slug:null, n:"VM05", title:"Sales, Persuasion & The Art of Influence", tagline:"Every founder is a salesperson. Every conversation is an opportunity to create momentum.", sub:"Deliverable: Sales Strategy · Partnership Outreach Plan · Complete Investor Pitch Deck · Rehearsed 8-Minute Presentation",
      body:"Founders do not simply build products. They convince customers to buy, partners to collaborate, investors to listen, employees to join, and communities to believe in a vision that does not yet exist.\n\nThis module explores the psychology and mechanics of influence, persuasion, negotiation, and sales. Students learn how trust is built, how buying decisions are made, why people say yes, and how successful entrepreneurs move people from interest to action.\n\nThe module combines practical sales training, customer conversations, negotiation strategy, partnership development, and investor communication. Students learn how to conduct discovery conversations, qualify opportunities, handle objections, negotiate confidently, build strategic relationships, and communicate value persuasively across a wide range of business situations.\n\nBy the end of the module, every student will have developed a complete investor pitch deck, delivered multiple rehearsals, refined their presentation style, and prepared to defend their venture under live questioning.",
      learn:["Sales psychology — understanding how customers evaluate and make decisions","Discovery conversations — asking questions that uncover needs, motivations, and objections","Persuasion psychology — trust, credibility, influence, and behavioral decision-making","Negotiation fundamentals — creating value while protecting interests","Objection handling — responding confidently to skepticism and concerns","Partnership development — approaching potential collaborators, advisors, sponsors, and stakeholders","Relationship capital — building long-term professional networks and opportunities","Investor pitch architecture — problem, solution, market, model, traction, team, and ask","Storytelling for founders — turning a venture into a compelling narrative rather than a collection of facts","Slide design and presentation structure — building professional investor-ready pitch decks","Executive presence — confidence, composure, body language, and delivery under pressure","High-pressure Q&A mastery — handling investor, customer, and stakeholder questions with clarity and precision","Closing and commitment — moving conversations from interest to action, support, investment, or partnership"] },
    { slug:null, n:"VM06", title:"Financial Modeling for Founders", tagline:"Strong ventures are built on sound financial assumptions, not guesswork.", sub:"Deliverable: Complete Financial Model · Revenue Projections · Cost Structure · 18-Month P&L",
      body:"Great founders do not need to be accountants, but they must understand the numbers that drive their business. This module teaches students how to translate a venture idea into a financial model investors, partners, and advisors can actually evaluate.\n\nStudents learn how revenue is generated, what it costs to operate, how margins are calculated, how much capital is needed, and how long a company can survive before it runs out of cash. They build realistic assumptions instead of fantasy projections and learn how small changes in pricing, costs, conversion rates, or customer acquisition can dramatically affect the business.\n\nThe module also introduces students to the financial questions investors care about most: Can this business make money? Can it scale? How much does it cost to acquire a customer? How long is the runway? What must be true for this venture to work?\n\nBy the end of the module, students will have built a founder-level financial model with revenue projections, cost structure, unit economics, scenario assumptions, and an 18-month profit-and-loss forecast.",
      learn:["Revenue modeling — building bottom-up projections from real assumptions","Pricing strategy — understanding how price affects demand, margin, and positioning","Unit economics — CAC, LTV, contribution margin, and payback period","Cost structure — fixed costs, variable costs, operating expenses, and burn rate","Runway and cash planning — understanding how long a venture can operate before needing more capital","Break-even analysis — identifying when revenue can cover expenses","Scenario planning — modeling base case, upside case, and downside case outcomes","Profit-and-loss fundamentals — revenue, expenses, gross margin, operating income, and net profit","Investor assumptions — understanding which financial claims investors challenge first","Cap table basics — how equity is structured, diluted, and valued"] },
    { slug:null, n:"VM07", title:"Capital Raising & Funding Strategy", tagline:"From bootstrapping and Kickstarter to angel investors and later-stage capital rounds.", sub:"Deliverable: Full Funding Strategy · One-Page Fundraising Brief",
      body:"Founders can access funding from many sources throughout a company’s growth journey, including family and friends, angel investors, startup accelerators, crowdfunding platforms like Kickstarter, seed funding, and later-stage venture capital rounds. Where that capital comes from, what it costs, and whether it is worth taking are critical strategic decisions.\n\nMany founders assume venture capital is the goal. In reality, successful businesses are funded in many different ways, and the smartest financing strategy depends on the venture itself. This module teaches students how capital flows through the entrepreneurial ecosystem, how investors evaluate opportunities, and how founders make financing decisions that support long-term growth.\n\nStudents explore the full funding landscape, from bootstrapping and customer-funded growth to angel investors, venture capital, grants, accelerators, strategic partnerships, and crowdfunding. They learn how ownership changes over time, what dilution actually means, how fundraising impacts control, and why not every dollar of investment is equal.\n\nThe module also introduces students to the legal and economic mechanics of fundraising, including SAFE notes, convertible notes, equity financing, valuations, term sheets, and investor expectations. Through case studies, venture analyses, and a live mock term sheet negotiation with an investor guest speaker, students gain a practical understanding of how founders raise capital and negotiate from a position of knowledge.\n\nBy the end of the module, students will have developed a funding strategy tailored to their venture, understand the implications of different financing paths, and be able to discuss fundraising with the confidence and vocabulary of an early-stage founder.",
      learn:["The funding landscape — bootstrapping, customer-funded growth, angels, venture capital, crowdfunding, grants, accelerators, and strategic partnerships","Founder-investor fit — understanding which funding sources are appropriate for different types of ventures","Venture capital fundamentals — how venture firms operate, invest, and generate returns","SAFE notes, convertible notes, and equity financing — how each structure works and when founders use them","Valuation fundamentals — what determines a company’s value and why valuations matter","Dilution and ownership — how investment affects founder equity and long-term control","Cap table mechanics — understanding ownership structure across multiple financing rounds","Investor psychology — what investors look for and what causes them to pass","Term sheets — the key clauses every founder should understand before accepting capital","Fundraising strategy — determining when to raise, how much to raise, and what capital is actually needed"] },
    { slug:null, n:"VM08", title:"Legal Foundations for Founders", tagline:"Know what you are signing before you sign it.", sub:"Outside Specialist — Practicing Attorney with Startup Experience",
      body:"Most founders do not make legal mistakes because they are careless. They make them because they do not yet know what can go wrong: the wrong entity, unclear ownership, missing IP protection, weak founder agreements, careless contracts, or terms they did not fully understand until it was too late.\n\nThis module gives students the legal literacy every young founder needs before building a venture. It is a practical introduction to the structures, documents, and decisions that shape the first years of a company.\n\nStudents learn how companies are formed, how ownership is divided, how intellectual property is protected, how contracts create obligations, and why the details of founder agreements, NDAs, equity terms, and term sheets matter before a serious business relationship begins.",
      learn:["Business entity types: LLC, C-corp, S-corp, sole proprietorship, and when each structure makes sense","Equity structure: ownership splits, dilution, vesting schedules, cliff periods, and what happens when a co-founder leaves","Founder agreements: roles, responsibilities, equity, decision rights, vesting, IP assignment, and dispute prevention","Intellectual property: trademarks, copyrights, patents, trade secrets, ownership, and protection of what students build","Contracts and NDAs: what makes an agreement binding, what clauses create risk, and what should never be signed casually","Employment and contractor basics: IP assignment, confidentiality, compensation, and early-team agreements","Term sheet basics: valuation, equity, liquidation preference, control rights, investor protections, and the clauses founders must understand","Cap tables: how ownership changes over time and why early mistakes become expensive later","How to work with a lawyer: what to ask, what to understand yourself, and when professional legal guidance is necessary"] },
  ];

